 1. Using the echo command print in console "Hello World". Here is some info about echo command

 Command_to_answer_the_question
 echo "Hello World"

2. Create a new directory called new_dir.

 Command_to_answer_the_question
 mkdir new_dir

3. Delete/Remove the directory new_dir.

 Command_to_answer_the_question
 rm -rf new_dir

 4. Copy the file sed.txt from the lorem folder and paste it to the folder lorem-copy folder.

 Command_to_answer_the_question
 cp lorem/sed.txt lorem-copy/

 5. Copy the other two files from the lorem folder to lorem-copy folder in just one line using semicolon ;

 Command_to_answer_the_question
  cp lorem/at.txt lorem/lorem.txt lorem-copy/;

6. Show the sed.txt file content from the lorem folder.

Command_to_answer_the_question
cat lorem/sed.txt

7. Show the at.txt file and lorem.txt file contents from lorem folder.

Command_to_answer_the_question
 cat lorem/at.txt lorem/lorem.txt

 8. Print the first 3 rows in sed.txt file from lorem-copy folder.

Command_to_answer_the_question
head -n 3 lorem-copy/sed.txt


9. Print the last 3 rows in sed.txt file from lorem-copy folder.

Command_to_answer_the_question
tail -n 3 lorem-copy/sed.txt


10. Add Homo homini lupus. at the end of sed.txt file in the lorem-copy folder.


Command_to_answer_the_question
 echo "Homo homini lupus" >> lorem-copy/sed.txt


 11. Print the last 3 rows in sed.txt file from lorem-copy folder. You should see Homo homini lupus.

 Command_to_answer_the_question
tail -n 3 lorem-copy/sed.txt

12. sed command is used to replace the text in a file. Use the sed command to replace all occurances of et with ET in the file at.txt file present in the folder lorem. You can use the following link to refer to sed commands [https://www.linode.com/docs/guides/manipulate-text-from-the-command-line-with-sed/] Check the 
contents of the sed.txt file using cat command.

Command_to_answer_the_question
sed -i 's/et/ET/g' lorem/at.txt

cat lorem/sed.txt 

13. Find who is the system user.

Command_to_answer_the_question
 git config user.name



14. Find the current path of the directory you are in.

Command_to_answer_the_question
pwd

15. List all files with the extension .txt in lorem folder.

Command_to_answer_the_question
 git ls-files 'lorem/*.txt'


16. Count the rows in sed.txt file from lorem folder. Look concatenate cat and wc with the pipe |.

Command_to_answer_the_question
cat lorem/sed.txt | wc -l


17. Count the files which start with lorem in all directories.

Command_to_answer_the_question
 git ls-files *lorem | wc -l

18. Store your name in a variable with read command.

Command_to_answer_the_question
read name

19. Print that variable.

Command_to_answer_the_question
echo $name

20. Create a new directory named with variable name.

Command_to_answer_the_question
 mkdir name

21.Remove that directory.

Command_to_answer_the_question
rm -rf name











